arch:property.oc:show_val: X1 and X2 are distal tibia points. This is fill of Space 227, which appears to include a minor component of redeposited bone that came with the fill (but not much; it was pretty clean) and mostly minimally processed feasting remains (and perhaps some daily meals as well?) dumped in during the filling. Sheep/goat may dominate slightly by count, but there is a lot of cattle. Sheep.goat MNI = 8 on right scapulae. Otherwise, a few specimens of dog and one each of boar and a small carnivore. In a moderate size unit, the paucity of taxa other than sheep, goat, and cattle is noteworthy. And perhaps this gives added significance to a large piece (ca. three-quarters) of a human tibia. It looks better preserved than is usual in burials, although hard to be sure; certainly not out of line with the surface condition of the rest of the unit. If any element is overrepresented, it is the tibia, raising the possibility of selection for some reason and potentially some kind of statement of equivalence between human and animals. Note that there are also two tibia points from the unit. Body part distribution is remarkably even for sheep-size. Vertebrae are more frequent than usual, although still probably somewhat underrepresented. All the meaty parts are there, and durable parts such as the distal humerus are not overrepresented while less dense parts are well represented. Small fragments are few, but no doubt because this is handpicked, and long bone shaft fragments are fewer than usual although certainly present. Cattle is slightly less evenly distributed through the body. There are some large mammal vertebrae, but not very many. Long bone shaft fragments are relatively few and ribs still more so, and here it is harder to attribute to handpicking. Given the low fragmentation of the diagnostics in both size ranges, there are probably genuinely few shaft fragments. Meaty parts are definitely present for cattle, notably tibiae, but they are somewhat tilted to the feet: metapodials and phalanges, indicating butchery waste. One of the metapodials is intact, but most long bones are broken for marrow. Both size ranges seem to have escaped bone grease processing. Cattle horn is notably absent, while sheep/goat horn is represented pretty much proportionately to the postcranial, including a wild ram. There are several complete or nearly complete scapulae of both cattle and sheep/goat; these seem roughly in proportion to the rest rather than special selections. There are some articulations among the cattle bones. Check for a possible bias to the the right side, at least among sheep/goat; certainly not exclusive. There is little digestion, although the handpicking will have affected that. There are some gnawed pieces, showing the feasting materials were gathered up for dumping after some exposure to dogs, or else were left open for a while. Since this is described as a fill with the bones distributed through it, the former seems more likely. Surface condition has suffered somewhat from proximity to the ground surface, but most seem to have gone in pretty fresh, with a small number of more worn fragments that likely came in with the fill. There is very little burning, most of it post-consumption low temperature exposure. At least one vertebra has what could be a roasting pattern. No microfauna, fish, or bird was present, but there is a bone point fragment. There seems to be no flotation sample. In sum, this looks like dumping of feasting remains, or certainly minimally processed meal remains (and some butchery discard) during the filling of the house. It is likely that this is tied to ceremonies marking the end of the house, or the beginning of the next. There are several sheep and goats and at least two cattle (one immature) represented, so it would have been a large and varied feast. As usual, we do not have the whole animals, so it may have been part of some larger house renewal event.
